      description:
          "The Mutawakkiliyah Kingdom of Yemen, also known as the Kingdom of Yemen or retrospectively as North Yemen, was a state that existed between 1918 and 1962 in the northern part of the country of Yemen now. The country's capital was Sana'a until 1948, when it was moved to Taiz. The religious leaders of the Zaidiyah, a group within Islam, succeeded in expelling the Ottoman Empire from northern Yemen in the mid-17th century, but after a century, Yemen's unity broke due to the difficulty of governing Yemen's mountainous regions. In 1849, the Ottoman Empire occupied the coastal Tihamah region to pressure the Zaidid Imams to sign the Ottoman suzerainity agreement and allow a small Ottoman army to be stationed in Sana'a. However, the Ottomans were slow to gain control of Yemen and were unable to eliminate resistance from the local Zaidis. In 1913, shortly before World War I, the Ottoman Empire was forced to cede territory to the Zaidis who lived in the highlands. On 30 October 1918, following the collapse of the Ottoman Empire, Imam Yahya Muhammad Hamiduddin of the al-Qasimi dynasty declared northern Yemen to be an independent sovereign state. In 1926, Imam Yahya proclaimed the Mutawakkiliyah Kingdom of Yemen, then he became king and religious leader (Zaidiyah), and managed to gain international recognition for his new country."),
