      description:
          "During the Asuka period (538-710), the ancient Japanese state of Yamato gradually became a centralized state. The ancient Japanese state already had laws as stated in the Taihō Law and the points of the Taika Reform. The arrival of Buddhism in Japan resulted in people no longer making kofun-shaped tombs. Buddhism entered Japan around 538 through Baekje which received military support from Japan. The spread of Buddhism in Japan was carried out by the ruling circles. Prince Shōtoku dedicated himself to the spread of Buddhism and Chinese culture in Japan. He is credited with drafting the 17-article Constitution which brought peace to Japan. The constitution he drafted was influenced by Confucian ideas about the morals and virtues that society expected of government officials and the emperor's servants. In a letter that the envoy of the Japanese Empire delivered to the Chinese Empire in 607 were written the words, \"The emperor of the land of the rising sun (Japan) sends a letter to the emperor of the land of the setting sun (China)\". The letter caused the anger of the Chinese emperor. Beginning with the Taika Reform Order in 645, Japan increasingly actively adopted Chinese cultural practices, reorganized the government, and drafted penal codes (Ritsuryō) following the Chinese administrative structure of the time. The term Nihon (日本) also came into use as a country name from Asuka's time."),
